pull_request.title: fix(playwright): replace duplicate FCP with FID
pull_request.body:
# What

Replacing duplicate `onFCP` Web Vital hook with the missing `onFID`.  
I believe the `FID` was mistakenly replaced with already present `FCP` [here](https://github.com/artilleryio/artillery/commit/675cb9252376a91c9f7f5680b82c672dda387bb1). **This was causing `FCP` to be emitted twice in the metrics**.

## Note
While I was looking into Web Vitals I read that:

> FID will be replaced by Interaction to Next Paint (INP) as a Core Web Vital in March 2024.

Should we also add a hook for `INP` ?

comment.body:
Hey @ematta , I believe I've managed to replicate the issue. I think the problem is that since you're using Artillery as a dependency, your lock files still kept dependant packages at an older version. 

You should be able to confirm this by running ```cat node_modules/@artilleryio/int-core/package.json | grep version``` in the path where your node_modules is (or if that doesn't work, try to find that package `@artilleryio/int-core` in your node_modules, and confirm which version it has in package.json).

If the version you see there is not [2.2.0](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@artilleryio/int-core/v/2.2.0), then you won't have `mean`, and that is causing the reporter to show that as `undefined`.

---

You should be able to resolve this by making sure that your lock files are updated. If nothing else works, I believe simply reinstalling artillery (uninstall then install v2.0.0-38 fresh) should work.

issue.title: `ifTrue` Unexpected Behaviours
issue.body:
I've found that when using `ifTrue` conditions within my test script, the behaviour of it does not match up to what is described in the [documentation](https://www.artillery.io/docs/reference/engines/http#conditional-requests).

**Version info:** 
```
VERSION INFO:

Artillery: 2.0.0-38
Node.js:   v18.18.2
OS:        linux
```
_I've also tested this against 2.0.0-34_

**Running this command:** 
```
export DEBUG=http
artillery run <fileName>
```
_I've exported DEBUG=http, to make it easier to see what requests are being made_

**I expected to see this happen:**

Based on the documentation, `ifTrue` can work in 2 different ways. I've got problems with both.

1) > Set to a name of a scenario variable. If the variable is set, the request will be executed.
	- In the below example I've provided, the variable `hit200: true` is defined, and I have an `ifTrue: "hit200"`. 
		- **It was called** - This was expected behaviour.
	- In the same example, I've defined `hit201: false`. I've again got a GET to `/201` with an `ifTrue: hit201`.
		- **The endpoint was not called** - I would have expected it to be called.
	- Based on the documentation i've linked & quoted, both of these should have behaved in the same way, since it was just checking if a variable is set(as I've done no other conditional checks). However, **it appears they're taking the value of the variable into account.**

---

2. > Set to a simple conditional expression, which may refer to any of the scenario variables...
	- I've set 2 variables, `hit300: true` and `hit301: false`. I then have 2 GET requests, one with `ifTrue: "hit300 == true"` and `ifTrue: "hit301 == false"`
		- **Neither of these were called.** - I would have expected both to have been based on the conditional logic.
	- I've set 2 variables, `hit400: true` and `hit401: false`. I then have 2 GET requests, this time referencing the variables using `vars.hit400` and `vars.hit401`.
		- **Both of these were called** - This is what I expected. The only difference between this and the above is the addition of the `vars` prefix(which isn't shown anywhere in the docs).
	- I've set `hit402: false`, and have a GET with `ifTrue: "not vars.hit402 == true"`.
		- **This endpoint was not called** - I would have expected it to be(Confusing negation, sorry!)


---

I think the above should explain this well enough(it's quite tricky to explain). But to summarise, we're seeing conditional logic not work the same way everywhere and not adhere to the documentation.

Files being used:
```yaml
config:
  variables:
    hit200: true
    hit201: false
    hit300: true
    hit301: false
    hit400: true
    hit401: false
    hit402: false
  target: https://http.cat
  phases:
    - duration: 5
      arrivalRate: 1
      maxVusers: 1
scenarios:
  - name: Test Scenario
    flow:
      - get:
          name: "Hit 200"
          url: "/200"
          ifTrue: "hit200"
      - get:
          name: "Hit 201"
          url: "/201"
          ifTrue: "hit201"
      - get:
          name: "Hit 300"
          url: "/300"
          ifTrue: "hit300 == true"
      - get:
          name: "Hit 301"
          url: "/301"
          ifTrue: "hit301 == false"
      - get:
          name: "Hit 400"
          url: "/400"
          ifTrue: "vars.hit400 == true"
      - get:
          name: "Hit 401"
          url: "/401"
          ifTrue: "vars.hit401 == false"
      - get:
          name: "Hit 402"
          url: "/402"
          ifTrue: "not vars.hit402 == true"
```

comment.body:
Hi @cjsaurusrex 👋 

Thanks for reporting this and for the thorough report as usual. It does seem that it's not working correctly. We'll look into this soon - I believe I know what might be wrong. Will post an update as soon as we have a fix!

Hi @ematta !

Thanks for reporting this. I'll take a look at this. Can you let me know if in the `json` report (`testrun.json`) that you generated, the `mean` was also showing up as undefined (or not appearing)? 

---

P.S. as I replied [here](https://github.com/artilleryio/artillery/discussions/2247#discussioncomment-7394517), still having the `includeFiles` in the config is probably why it's still doing the installs on Fargate!

issue.title: Fargate tasks not starting with "ResourceInitializationError: unable to pull secrets or registry auth"
issue.body:
I'm trying to use the new Fargate approach in eu-central-1. (The same test repo has been used with Artillery Pro in eu-west-2 before.)

I've confirmed I have a VPC in the region, 3 public subnets, and that Artillery is correctly automatically using those subnets, so I don't think [networking per se](https://stackoverflow.com/a/66802973/2803757) is the problem.

I've set up a user with the permissions [as documented today](https://www.artillery.io/docs/load-testing-at-scale/aws-fargate#iam-permissions). I created what's in the docs as a policy and attached this directly to a user group which my user is in – I wasn't totally clear how a role should be used if created.

It seems the `ecr:GetAuthorizationToken` is part of a policy that Artillery itself sets up via a worker role, and that's why it isn't in the documented policy to be set up manually in AWS. But I'm not sure what to try now to get it to run.

Version info: <!-- artillery -v output -->
```
Artillery: 2.0.0-37
Node.js:   v18.18.0
OS:        darwin
```

Running this command: 
```
artillery run-fargate --count 1 --region eu-central-1 --overrides '{\"config\": {\"phases\": [{\"duration\": 1, \"arrivalRate\": 1}]}}' --output reports/report.json --record api-donations.yaml
```

comment.body:
I think I've sorted this for our account.

I believe the problems were a combination of the all-or-nothing approach to the worker role creation, and 2 errors in the [Artillery docs for Fargate](https://www.artillery.io/docs/load-testing-at-scale/aws-fargate#iam-permissions) which meant some of the required permissions weren't there when enough of the IAM resources were repeatedly deleted for Artillery to attempt their recreation:

1. `arn:aws:iam::123456789000:policy/ecs-worker-policy` should be `arn:aws:iam::123456789000:policy/artilleryio-ecs-worker-policy`
2. `iam:AttachRolePolicy` is required for resource `arn:aws:iam::123456789000:role/artilleryio-ecs-worker-role`, not [just] for the policy
